                    CALIFORNIA LEGISLATURE—
                    2025–2026 REGULAR SESSION</font></div><br clear="all"/><span id="bill_house_num"><div style="float: left; width:50%; font-weight: bold; "><span style="text-transform: uppercase; text-align:left;width:50%;"><b>
                Senate Bill
              </b></span></div><div style="float:right; width:50%; text-align:right;"><span style="text-transform: uppercase;"><b>No. 1181</b></span></div></span><hr/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td id="bill_authors" align="center"><span style="font-weight:bold;">Introduced by Senator Hurtado<br/></span></td></tr><tr><td id="bill_intro_date" align="center" class="textcenter"><br/>February 18, 2026</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr/><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;">An act to add Article 5.1 (commencing with Section 233.9) to Chapter 2 of Part 1 of Division 1 of Title 1 of the Education Code, relating to school safety.</span></div><br clear="all"/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">SB 1181, as amended, Hurtado.
                          <font color="#B30000"><strike>Central Valley </strike></font>Violence Prevention,<font color="#B30000"><strike> Student</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> Pupil</i></font> Wellness, and School Safety Grant<font color="#B30000"><strike> Pilot</strike></font> Program.</span></div><div><span id="digesttext"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Existing law establishes the State Department of Education in state government, and vests the department with specified powers and duties relating to the state’s public school system. Existing law declares the policy of the state to ensure that all local educational agencies work to reduce violence, improve pupil safety at schools, and improve the connections between pupils and supportive adults, schools, and communities.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This bill would require the<font color="#B30000"><strike> State Department of Education,</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> department,</i></font> in consultation with the Office of Emergency Services, to establish and administer the<font color="#B30000"><strike> Central Valley</strike></font>
		Violence Prevention,<font color="#B30000"><strike> Student</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> Pupil</i></font> Wellness, and School Safety Grant<font color="#B30000"><strike> Pilot</strike></font> Program to, upon appropriation by the Legislature, award grants to eligible<font color="#B30000"><strike> entities located in certain counties,</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> school districts, county offices of education, or charter schools</i></font> for evidence-based violence prevention,<font color="#B30000"><strike> student</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> pupil</i></font> wellness, and public safety initiatives, as
		specified. The bill would require the department to consult with representatives of the office, local educational agencies, county behavioral health departments, community-based organizations, and<font color="#B30000"><strike> law enforcement</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> public safety</i></font>
		agencies when it develops guidelines for the program. The bill would<font color="#B30000"><strike> also</strike></font> require each grant recipient to submit findings to the department on the effectiveness of its activities funded by the grant<font color="#B30000"><strike> which shall be used by</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> and would require</i></font> the department<font color="#B30000"><strike> in</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> to use those findings to prepare and submit</i></font> a report to the Legislature<font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> on or before January 1, 2029,</i></font> evaluating the effectiveness of the grant program and providing recommendations
		regarding violence prevention,<font color="#B30000"><strike> student</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>
		pupil</i></font> wellness, school safety, and behavioral health<font color="#B30000"><strike> investments in the central valley,
			 on or before January 1, 2029.</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> investments.</i></font></div><font color="#B30000"><strike><p style="display:inline;"><s>This bill would make legislative findings and declarations as to the necessity of a special statute for the Counties of Fresno, Kern, Kings, Tulare, Madera, Merced, San Joaquin, and Stanislaus.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font></span></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span><span id="vote">
      Vote:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">MAJORITY</span>  </span><span id="appropriation">
      Appropriation:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span><span id="fiscalcommittee">
      Fiscal Committee:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">YES</span>  </span><span id="localprogram">
      Local Program:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><div id="bill"><div style=" text-transform: uppercase"><h2 style=" text-align: left;">The people of the State of California do enact as follows:</h2><br/></div><font color="#B30000"><strike><caml:BillSection id="id_797A94EA-6D67-4032-920D-2C60456DA891"><div style="margin:0 0 0.5em 0;"></div><caml:Num>SECTION 1.</caml:Num><caml:Content><p style="display:inline;"><s>The Legislature finds and declares all of the following:</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(a)<span class="EnSpace"/>Tragic incidents of teenage shooting deaths in the Central Valley, including Senate District 16 areas, demonstrate broader trends of escalating gun violence
				and youth involvement in firearm-related threats. For example, in Hanford in the County of Kings, 17-year-old Ayden Anthony Wyatt was fatally shot at the
				Casa del Sol Apartments in January 2026, leading to arrests and underscoring risks from gun violence in school-adjacent communities.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(b)<span class="EnSpace"/>Similar violence has affected nearby regions, including in Clovis in the County of Fresno portion of Senate District 16, where 18-year-old Caleb Quick was killed outside a McDonald’s in April 2025 by two 16-year-old suspects, and a 15-year-old boy died in a December 2025 accidental shooting, exemplifying trends of youth access to firearms contributing to preventable fatalities and school safety concerns.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(c)<span class="EnSpace"/>In the County of Kern, multiple teenage fatalities from shootings illustrate pervasive trends of gun violence impacting youth mental health and community stability in rural areas, including all of the following:</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(1)<span class="EnSpace"/>Fifteen-year-old Prince Michael Banner was killed at The
				Marketplace in November 2024, with a 16-year-old arrested. </s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(2)<span class="EnSpace"/>A 12-year-old boy was murdered in Lamont in October 2024, with a juvenile admitting to the crime.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(d)<span class="EnSpace"/>The proliferation of untraceable ghost guns exacerbates these trends, as seen in incidents like the February 2026 discovery of an 18-year-old in nearby San Jose manufacturing 27 ghost guns using 3D printers, highlighting how easily accessible technology enables youth involvement in firearm-related threats within the broader Central Valley region.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(e)<span class="EnSpace"/>Social media’s role in perpetuating harm demonstrates trends of online hate impacting youth
				futures and school environments. For example, in February 2026 at Redwood High School in Visalia in the County of Tulare, students arranged shirts to spell a homophobic slur in a viral photo, leading to investigations, community backlash, and long-term online stigma that could hinder the futures of involved students while making LGBTQ+ youth feel unsafe and unwelcome in schools.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(f)<span class="EnSpace"/>It is the intent of the Legislature to enact legislation to protect the mental health, safety, and well-being of children and adolescents in California, particularly in underserved areas like Senate
				District 16, by addressing the growing impact of AI, digital technologies, and emerging threats on youths’ mental health development through improved coordination and privacy-protected information sharing.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></caml:Content></caml:BillSection></strike></font><div id="s20.7806815650044576"><div><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;"><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>SECTION 1.</i></font></h3> (a) The Legislature finds and declares all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Safe schools and communities are essential to pupil success, academic achievement, workforce development, and economic prosperity.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Communities throughout California continue to experience challenges related to youth violence, chronic absenteeism, behavioral health needs, substance abuse, gang involvement, and emerging digital threats affecting youth and families.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) School safety, violence prevention, and pupil well-being are interconnected and require coordinated efforts among educators, families, behavioral health professionals, community organizations, emergency management professionals, and law enforcement agencies.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(4) Evidence-based violence prevention, early intervention, mentoring, counseling, and behavioral health services have been shown to improve educational outcomes, reduce violence, and increase community safety.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(5) Community-based organizations and local governments play a critical role in preventing violence before it occurs and connecting youth and families with needed support services.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(6) Some community-based organizations providing violence prevention and behavioral health services have
		  experienced reductions or uncertainty in available funding, creating challenges in maintaining prevention-focused programs.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) It is the intent of the Legislature to support a comprehensive public safety strategy that addresses both the root causes of violence and the need for safe school and community environments.</div></i></font></div></div><div id="s30.5478045425241537"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0" class="ActionLine"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;">SEC. 2.</h3> Article 5.1 (commencing with Section 233.9) is added to Chapter 2 of Part 1 of Division 1 of Title 1 of the Education Code, to read:</div><div><div><div id="id_EAA29B1C-734B-4F5E-8C29-675C8D081271"><div><h5 style="text-align:left;">
                Article
               5.1. <font color="#B30000"><strike>Central Valley </strike></font>Violence Prevention,<font color="#B30000"><strike> Student</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> Pupil</i></font> Wellness, and School Safety Grant<font color="#B30000"><strike> Pilot</strike></font> Program</h5></div></div><font color="#B30000"><strike><caml:LawSection id="id_D9303ED2-7E68-47AA-BBC7-CF41C86A12F9"><div style="margin:0 0 0.5em 0;"></div><caml:Num>233.9.</caml:Num><caml:LawSectionVersion id="id_4712A1BC-4B82-4068-8349-5A8BBEDD4C3E"><caml:Content><p style="display:inline;"><s>The Legislature finds and declares all of the following:</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(a)<span class="EnSpace"/>Safe schools and communities are essential to student success, academic achievement, workforce development, and economic prosperity.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(b)<span class="EnSpace"/>Communities throughout California’s central valley continue to experience challenges related to youth violence, chronic absenteeism, behavioral health needs, substance abuse, gang involvement, and emerging digital threats affecting youth and families.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(c)<span class="EnSpace"/>School safety, violence prevention, and student well-being are interconnected and require coordinated efforts among educators, families, behavioral health professionals, community organizations, emergency management professionals, and law enforcement agencies.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(d)<span class="EnSpace"/>Evidence-based violence prevention, early intervention, mentoring, counseling, and behavioral health services have been shown to improve educational outcomes, reduce violence, and increase community safety.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(e)<span class="EnSpace"/>Community-based organizations and local governments play a critical role in preventing violence before it occurs and connecting youth and families with needed support services.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(f)<span class="EnSpace"/>Some community-based organizations providing violence prevention and behavioral health services have experienced reductions or uncertainty in available
						  funding, creating challenges in maintaining prevention-focused programs.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(g)<span class="EnSpace"/>It is the intent of the Legislature to support a comprehensive public safety strategy that addresses both the root causes of violence and the need for safe school and community environments.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></caml:Content></caml:LawSectionVersion></caml:LawSection></strike></font><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;"><font color="#B30000"><strike>233.9.1.</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>233.9.</i></font></h6> (a) The<font color="#B30000"><strike> State Department of Education,</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> department,</i></font> in consultation with the Office of Emergency Services, shall establish and administer the<font color="#B30000"><strike> Central Valley</strike></font> Violence Prevention,<font color="#B30000"><strike> Student</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>
					 Pupil</i></font> Wellness, and School Safety Grant<font color="#B30000"><strike> Pilot</strike></font>
					 Program.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) Upon appropriation by the Legislature, the program shall award grants to eligible<font color="#B30000"><strike> entities located within the Counties of Fresno, Kern, Kings, Madera, Merced, San Joaquin, Stanislaus, and Tulare.</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> local educational agencies.</i></font></div><font color="#B30000"><strike><p style="display:inline;"><s>(c)<span class="EnSpace"/>Eligible applicants shall include all of the following:</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(1)<span class="EnSpace"/>Local educational agencies.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(2)<span class="EnSpace"/>County offices of education.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(3)<span class="EnSpace"/>Community-based organizations.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(4)<span class="EnSpace"/>Local governments.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(5)<span class="EnSpace"/>Tribal governments.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(6)<span class="EnSpace"/>Partnerships consisting of one or more of the entities identified in this subdivision.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) Eligible applicants are encouraged to collaborate with community-based organizations, local governmental agencies, and tribal governments when applying for a grant under the program.</div></i></font><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(d) Grant funds may be used for evidence-based violence prevention,<font color="#B30000"><strike> student</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> pupil</i></font> wellness, and public safety initiatives, including, but not limited to, any of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) School-based mental health<font color="#B30000"><strike> services.</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> services provided by school counselors,
					 school psychologists, and school social workers.</i></font></div><font color="#B30000"><strike><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(2)<span class="EnSpace"/>School counselors, school psychologists, and school social workers.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(3)</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2)</i></font> Youth mentoring and positive youth development programs.</div><font color="#B30000"><strike><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(4)</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3)</i></font> Violence interruption and violence intervention programs.</div><font color="#B30000"><strike><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(5)</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(4)</i></font> Behavioral health outreach and support services.</div><font color="#B30000"><strike><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(6)</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(5)</i></font> Restorative justice and conflict resolution programs.</div><font color="#B30000"><strike><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(7)</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(6)</i></font> Programs designed to improve school attendance and<font color="#B30000"><strike> student</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> pupil</i></font> engagement.</div><font color="#B30000"><strike><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(8)</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(7)</i></font> Suicide prevention and crisis intervention services.</div><font color="#B30000"><strike><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(9)<span class="EnSpace"/>Training  for</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(8) Behavioral health training for</i></font> educators, behavioral health professionals, and youth-serving personnel.</div><font color="#B30000"><strike><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(10)<span class="EnSpace"/>Gang prevention and youth diversion programs.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(11)<span class="EnSpace"/>Community violence reduction initiatives.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(12)<span class="EnSpace"/>School safety planning and
						  emergency preparedness activities.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(13)<span class="EnSpace"/>Development of multidisciplinary threat assessment and violence prevention teams.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(14)<span class="EnSpace"/>Programs that strengthen collaboration between schools, community organizations, behavioral health providers, and local law enforcement agencies.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(15)<span class="EnSpace"/>Youth engagement, mentorship, and prevention-focused partnerships involving local law enforcement agencies.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(e) In awarding grants, the department shall prioritize programs that do all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Serve communities with demonstrated needs related to youth violence, chronic absenteeism, behavioral health challenges, or public safety concerns.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) <font color="#B30000"><strike>Utilize </strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>Use </i></font>evidence-based or promising practices.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) Demonstrate collaboration among schools, community organizations, behavioral health providers, and public safety partners.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(4) Address the needs of underserved or rural communities.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(f) The department shall consult with representatives of the Office of Emergency Services, local educational agencies, county behavioral health departments,
					 community-based organizations, and<font color="#B30000"><strike> law enforcement</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> public safety</i></font> agencies when<font color="#B30000"><strike> it</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> the department</i></font> develops guidelines for the program.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(g) (1) On or before January 1, 2029, the department shall submit a report to the Legislature evaluating the effectiveness of the grant program and providing recommendations regarding violence prevention,<font color="#B30000"><strike> student</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> pupil</i></font>
					 wellness, school safety, and behavioral health<font color="#B30000"><strike> investments in the central valley.</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> investments.</i></font> Each grant recipient shall submit findings to the department on the effectiveness of its activities funded by the grant which shall be used by the department to prepare the report. To the extent that it is feasible, the report shall also include all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(A) The number and type of grants awarded.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) The populations served by the program.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) The outcomes achieved by the program.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(D) Best practices identified via the program.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(E) Recommendations for future investments in violence prevention, public safety, and<font color="#B30000"><strike> student</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> pupil</i></font> wellness programs.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) (A) The requirement for submitting a report imposed under paragraph (1) is inoperative on January 1, 2033, pursuant to Section 10231.5 of the Government Code.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) A report to be submitted pursuant to paragraph (1) shall be submitted in compliance with Section 9795 of the Government Code.</div><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(h) For purposes of this
					 section, “local educational agency” means a school district, county office of education, or charter school.</div></i></font></p></div></div></div></div><font color="#B30000"><strike><caml:BillSection id="id_96FEC225-3A25-4B54-A396-2FAE30DCBC99"><div style="margin:0 0 0.5em 0;"></div><caml:Num>SEC. 3.</caml:Num><caml:Content><p style="display:inline;"><s>The Legislature finds and declares that a special statute is necessary and that a general statute cannot be made applicable within the meaning of Section 16 of Article IV of the California Constitution because of unique challenges related to youth safety, chronic absenteeism, and emerging digital threats that face the central valley, including the Counties of Fresno, Kern, Kings, Tulare, Madera, Merced, San Joaquin, and Stanislaus.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></caml:Content></caml:BillSection></strike></font></div></div></body></html>
